\begin_layout Standard
When acquiring an R&D company, part of the price will be for projects which
 do not pefrom at the moment (but are supposed to in the future).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When buying a company, we buy the performing projects, its infrastructure,
 but also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in-process R&D
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 When allocating some of the cost for that, it will initially appear as
 an 
\series bold
asset
\series default
 in the B/S.
 As time goes by, this asset is consumed and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

converted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike that, when doing our 
\series bold
own
\series default
 R/D - it is considered an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

expense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and usually cannot be listed as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asset
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, because of accounting conservatism (rules say to do so, because of uncertainit
y regarding whether it will bring future revenue).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When applying the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

creative acquisition technique
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - in year 1 the earnings will be worse, but expenses can be written off
 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

acquisition costs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 But afterwards the performance will be better in this option.
