\begin_layout Subsubsection
Premature Recognition of Revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of what we did so far was to delay income (report higher income in
 the future).
 Now we will go the other way round.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example with Xerox: the contracts are in form of 
\series bold
lease
\series default
.
 Signing a contract with a large corporation to install and maintain copy
 machines in all its branches.
 From accounting perspective, some of that money will be recorded as revenue,
 and the remaining part is unearned revenue.
 As time passes, it becomes revenue.
 A crucial part here is that the contract includes 
\series bold
future
\series default
 components.
 Taking it to the extreme, one can get the cash and record the whole amount
 as a revenue.
 In this way, instead of spreading it over time, it can be immediately recognize
d.
 It is 
\series bold
illegal
\series default
 (Xerox paid the largest financial fraud penalty ever).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Q1 '97 Xerox performed slightly above market expectations, which lead
 to even higherer expectations for the future, thus they started 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

making up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 earnings.
 From the manager's perspective the incentive is that they are judged on
 a short-term basis.
 Yet from accounting perspective, it obviously cannot be done forever (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

burning up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 future abilities).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the firm perspective: as black and white printing declined, Xerox suffered.
 They were sure that color printing would be the next big thing, and prepared
 for that technologically.
 Expecting a large profit in the future, they didn't want to disappoint
 investors.
 The problem was that these revenues never came.
 Xerox could not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 it, because the stock price would fall, thus they got 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stuck
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with this practice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This accounting scheme allowed Xerox to meet Wall Street's earnings targets.
 The stock price was kept artificially high, and executives cashed huge
 performance-based bonuses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the cash was not an issue here, but the accounting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Capitalizing Normal Operating Costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Costs incurred today which will benefit 
\series bold
only today
\series default
 are 
\series bold
expenses
\series default
.
 But, if they are assumed to 
\series bold
yield revenues
\series default
 in the next 5 years - they can be written initially as an 
\series bold
asset
\series default
 (capitalizing it), and then taken down every year (using it) - for example,
 a big spending on building the company brand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the AOL case with capitalization of its advertising costs.
 It was using a statement created for another industry (DMAC - deferred
 membership acquisition costs, intended for catalog companies).
 As accounting for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

brand name
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is impossible, they needed to use another name.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incentive for AOL was 
\series bold
overstating operating performance
\series default
.
\end_layout

